  "local_port": 54126,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Where do I start when looking for colleges?",
  "response": "Starting your college search can feel overwhelming, but breaking it down into manageable steps can help streamline the process. Here\u2019s a guide to get you started:\n\n1. **Self-Assessment**: \n   - Consider your academic interests, career goals, and personal values. \n   - Think about what type of environment you thrive in (urban vs. rural, large vs. small, etc.).\n   - Reflect on extracurricular activities and interests that you want to pursue in college.\n\n2. **Research**:\n   - Look into different types of colleges (liberal arts colleges, universities, community colleges, technical schools).\n   - Use online resources like college search websites (College Board, Niche, and U.S. News & World Report) to find lists of colleges that match your interests.\n   - Read college guides and reviews to get a sense of campus culture and academics.\n\n3. **Set Criteria**: \n   - Determine what's important to you, such as:\n     - Location (in-state, out-of-state, distance from home)\n     - Size (student population)\n     - Programs offered (major/minor options)\n     - Campus culture and social scene\n     - Cost and financial aid options\n     - Support services (tutoring, counseling, internships)\n\n4. **Create a Preliminary List**: \n   - Narrow down your options to a list of schools that meet your criteria. Aim for a mix of reach, match, and safety schools.\n\n5. **Visit Colleges**: \n   - Schedule campus visits to get a feel for the atmosphere.\n   - Attend information sessions and take guided tours.\n   - If possible, talk to current students and faculty to gain insights.\n\n6. **Admissions Requirements**: \n   - Research application requirements for each school, including GPA, standardized test scores (SAT/ACT), letters of recommendation, and personal essays.\n   - Note deadlines for applications, financial aid, and scholarships.\n\n7. **Financial Planning**: \n   - Investigate the cost of attendance (tuition, room and board, fees).\n   - Explore financial aid options including scholarships, grants, and loans.\n   - Use net price calculators available on college websites to estimate costs.\n\n8. **Prepare Application Materials**: \n   - Start drafting your personal statement or essays early.\n   - Request letters of recommendation from teachers or mentors in advance.\n   - Make sure your resume or list of activities is up-to-date.\n\n9. **Stay Organized**: \n   - Keep a spreadsheet or planner to track deadlines, requirements, and your thoughts on each school.\n   - Set aside time to focus on your applications and stay on top of each school's requirements.\n\n10. **Seek Support**: \n    - Talk to your school counselor for guidance and resources.\n    - Involve family and friends in your discussions to gain different perspectives.\n\n11. **Submit Applications**: \n    - Complete your applications before the deadlines.\n    - Ensure all components are polished and proofread.\n\n12. **Evaluate Offers**: \n    - Once you receive admissions decisions, compare financial aid packages and consider where you feel most comfortable.\n\nBy following these steps, you can effectively navigate your college search and find institutions that align with your goals and preferences. Good luck!",
